      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What costs can I claim to reduce capital gains tax when selling a property in Brisbane?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "When selling an investment property in Brisbane, you can reduce your capital gain by adding incidental costs of disposal to the cost base. These include real estate agent commission, conveyancer or solicitor fees for the sale, auctioneer fees, advertising and marketing costs you paid as the vendor, and any valuation fees obtained specifically for the purpose of selling. You can also add to the cost base the costs you paid when you bought the property, including stamp duty, legal fees, and buyer's agent fees. Capital improvements made during ownership, such as extensions or structural renovations, also increase the cost base. You cannot include routine repairs and maintenance, insurance, or council rates, as those are typically claimed as income deductions against rental income in the year they were paid."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is real estate agent commission tax deductible when selling a property in Brisbane?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Real estate agent commission is not a tax deduction in the traditional income tax sense, but it does reduce the taxable capital gain you make on the sale. Under Australian tax law, agent commission is an incidental cost of disposal that forms part of the cost base of a CGT asset. This means it is subtracted from your capital proceeds before your gain is calculated. For a Brisbane investment property selling for $1.2 million with a $30,000 agent commission, that commission reduces your assessable capital gain by $30,000. If you are selling your main residence and the full main residence exemption applies, agent commission has no tax effect because you pay no CGT regardless."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What records do I need to keep when selling an investment property in Brisbane?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "You should keep records of every cost that forms part of your cost base for at least five years after you lodge the tax return for the year of sale. This includes the original contract of sale when you bought the property, settlement statements from purchase and sale, invoices for agent commission and marketing costs, solicitor or conveyancer invoices from both purchase and sale, building and pest inspection fees from acquisition, invoices for capital improvements made during ownership, and any loan establishment fees that relate to the original acquisition. The ATO can review CGT calculations for five years from the date of lodgement. Missing records usually result in a higher assessed gain."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>

